+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MxwzKKSB6i6jNnE5Ho2fnF","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# T15: Permission Maze\n     2→\n     3→**Category:** greenfield/complex\n     4→**Timeout:** 30 minutes\n     5→\n     6→## Objective\n     7→\n     8→Build a document management API using Express and Node.js. The system manages users, hierarchical folders, documents, and granular sharing permissions. All storage should be in-memory (no database required).\n     9→\n    10→## Core Features\n    11→\n    12→### 1. User Management\n    13→\n    14→- **Register** a new user with username and password\n    15→- **Login** to receive an authentication token\n    16→- Token-based auth: all subsequent requests include the token (via `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header)\n    17→\n    18→### 2. Folders\n    19→\n    20→- Create, read, update, delete folders\n    21→- Folders can be nested inside other folders (hierarchical structure)\n    22→- Each folder has a name and an optional parent folder\n    23→\n    24→### 3. Documents\n    25→\n    26→- Create, read, update, delete documents inside folders\n    27→- Each document has a title, content (text), and belongs to a folder\n    28→- The creator of a document is its owner\n    29→\n    30→### 4. Sharing & Permissions\n    31→\n    32→Three roles: **viewer**, **editor**, **owner**\n    33→\n    34→- **Viewer**: can read the resource\n    35→- **Editor**: can read and modify the resource, and share it with others\n    36→- **Owner**: full control including deletion and role management\n    37→\n    38→Share folders or documents with other users by assigning them a role. The creator of a resource is automatically its owner.\n    39→\n    40→When a user has access to a resource through multiple paths (e.g., direct share + folder share), their effective permission should reflect the most permissive role granted.\n    41→\n    42→### 5. Activity Log\n    43→\n    44→Track actions performed in the system:\n    45→- Document creation, updates, deletion\n    46→- Sharing events\n    47→- Each log entry records the action type, the user who performed it, the target resource, and a timestamp\n    48→\n    49→## API Design\n    50→\n    51→Build a RESTful API. You choose the exact route structure, but it should be intuitive and consistent. Common patterns:\n    52→\n    53→- `POST /users` or `POST /auth/register` -- register\n    54→- `POST /auth/login` or `POST /login` -- login\n    55→- `POST /folders` -- create folder\n    56→- `GET /folders/:id` -- get folder\n    57→- `POST /documents` or `POST /folders/:folderId/documents` -- create document\n    58→- `GET /documents/:id` -- get document\n    59→- `POST /share` or `POST /:resourceType/:id/share` -- share resource\n    60→- `GET /activity` -- get activity log\n    61→\n    62→Return appropriate HTTP status codes (200, 201, 204, 400, 404, etc.).\n    63→\n    64→## Technical Requirements\n    65→\n    66→- Use Express.js\n    67→- In-memory storage (Maps, arrays, plain objects -- your choice)\n    68→- Export a `createApp()` function from your main module (`src/index.ts`, `src/app.ts`, or `src/server.ts`) that returns the Express app instance\n    69→- TypeScript\n    70→- All data resets when the server restarts (no persistence needed)\n    71→\n    72→## Provided Files\n    73→\n    74→- `package.json` -- dependencies configured\n    75→- `tsconfig.json`, `.eslintrc.cjs`, `vitest.config.ts` -- build/test config\n    76→\n    77→## Validation\n    78→\n    79→```bash\n    80→npm run build   # TypeScript compilation must succeed\n    81→npm run lint    # ESLint must pass\n    82→npm test        # Tests must pass\n    83→```\n    84→\n    85→Write your own tests to verify behavior as you build.\n    86→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01W9vCAExMUMstH23iHnPcGy","session_id":"82bc402b-6f66-43eb-81aa-8fc76b5c168d","uuid":"f6609570-3ded-49f6-b03e-15d4a352105d"}
